[30;1m1 | [0m[35m"""Utilities for inspecting a model's type.[0m

[30;1m36 | [0m[35m    Since River does not support an actual "off-line" phase of the clustering algorithm (as data[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35m    points are assumed to arrive continuously, one at a time), a `time_gap` parameter is introduced.[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35m    After each `time_gap`, an incremental K-Means clustering algorithm will be initialized and[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35m    applied on currently available micro-clusters to form the final solution, i.e. macro-clusters.[0m
[30;1m40 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m12 | [0m[35m    The CluStream algorithm [^1] maintains statistical information about the[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m    data using micro-clusters. These micro-clusters are temporal extensions of[0m

[30;1m94 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m95 | [0m[35m        # Update the weights[0m
[30;1m96 | [0m[35m        weights_gradient = self._calculate_weights_gradients(x, g_loss)[0m
[30;1m97 | [0m[35m        self.weights = self.weight_optimizer.step(w=self.weights, g=weights_gradient)[0m
[30;1m98 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m10 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35m    This is a wrapper that can be applied to any stochastic gradient descent optimiser. Note that[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35m    this implementation differs than what may be found elsewhere. Essentially, the average of the[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m    weights is usually only used at the end of the optimisation, once all the data has been seen.[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35m    However, in this implementation the optimiser returns the current averaged weights.[0m

[30;1m482 | [0m[35m    The online Extra Trees[^1] ensemble takes some steps further into randomization when[0m
[30;1m483 | [0m[35m    compared to Adaptive Random Forests (ARF). A subspace of the feature space is considered[0m
[30;1m484 | [0m[35m    at each split attempt, as ARF does, and online bagging or subbagging can also be[0m

[30;1m152 | [0m[35m## 🤔 Should I be using River?[0m
[30;1m153 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m154 | [0m[35mYou should ask yourself if you need online machine learning. The answer is likely no. Most of the ti[0m
[30;1m155 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m156 | [0m[35m- You want a model that can learn from new data without having to revisit past data.[0m
[30;1m157 | [0m[35m- You want a model which is robust to [concept drift](https://www.wikiwand.com/en/Concept_drift).[0m

[30;1m1 | [0m[35m"""River is a library for incremental learning. Incremental learning is a machine learning regime[0m
[30;1m2 | [0m[35mwhere the observations are made available one by one. It is also known as online learning,[0m
[30;1m3 | [0m[35miterative learning, or sequential learning. This is in contrast to batch learning where all the[0m
[30;1m4 | [0m[35mdata is processed at once. Incremental learning is desirable when the data is too big to fit in[0m
[30;1m5 | [0m[35mmemory, or simply when it isn't available all at once. river's API is heavily inspired from that of[0m
[30;1m6 | [0m[35mscikit-learn, enough so that users who are familiar with scikit-learn should feel right at home.[0m
[30;1m7 | [0m[35m"""[0m

[30;1m22 | [0m[35m        The discount factor to apply to the entropy measure. A value of 1 won't affect the entropy.[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35m        The higher the discount factor, the more the entropy will be discounted, and the less[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35m        likely samples will be selected for labeling. A value of 0 will select all samples for[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35m        labeling. The discount factor is thus a way to control how many samples are selected for[0m

[30;1m18 | [0m[35m    Bloom filters store a bit array and map incoming items to `k` index positions in the such array.[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35m    The selected positions are set to `True`. Therefore, a binary code representation is created for[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m    Membership works by projecting the query item and checking if every position of its binary code [0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35m    `True`. If that is not the case, the item was not observed yet. A nice property of Bloom filters[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35m    that they do not yield false negatives: unobserved items might be signalized as observed, but ob[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35m    items are never signalized as unobserved.[0m

[30;1m12 | [0m[35m    idea is to compute the quantiles of the residuals of the regressor. The prediction interval is[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m    then computed as the prediction of the regressor plus the quantiles of the residuals.[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35m    This works naturally online, as the quantiles of the residuals are updated at each iteration.[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35m    Each residual is produced before the regressor is updated, which ensures the predicted intervals[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35m    are not optimistic.[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m19 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m    Local Adaptive Streaming Tree [^1] (LAST) is an incremental decision tree with[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35m    adaptive splitting mechanisms. LAST maintains a change detector at each leaf and splits[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35m    this node if a change is detected in the error or the leaf`s data distribution.[0m

[30;1m20 | [0m[35m    Local Adaptive Streaming Tree [^1] (LAST) is an incremental decision tree with[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35m    adaptive splitting mechanisms. LAST maintains a change detector at each leaf and splits[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35m    this node if a change is detected in the error or the leaf`s data distribution.[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35m    LAST is still not suitable for use as a base classifier in ensembles due to the change detectors[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35m    The authors in [^1] are working on a version of LAST that overcomes this limitation.[0m

[30;1m1 | [0m[35m"""Evaluation metrics.[0m
[30;1m2 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m3 | [0m[35mAll the metrics are updated one sample at a time. This way we can track performance of[0m
[30;1m4 | [0m[35mpredictive methods over time.[0m
[30;1m5 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m6 | [0m[35mNote that all metrics have a `revert` method, enabling them to be wrapped in `utils.Rolling`.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m2188[0m[34m of [0m[33m2433[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m157 | [0m[35m    This current implementation within `River`, based on the original one in the paper, follows the [0m
[30;1m158 | [0m[35m        1) Insert new data points (`NewPoints`) and calculate its distance to existing points;[0m
[30;1m159 | [0m[35m        2) Update the nreaest neighboors and reverse nearest neighboors of all the points;[0m
[30;1m160 | [0m[35m        3) Define sets of affected points that required updates;[0m

[30;1m96 | [0m[35mNow let's run the model on the dataset in a streaming fashion. We sequentially interleave prediction[0m
